is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase gene", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9938738346099854, "span": {"begin": 870, "end": 884}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:8128"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Nile tilapia", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8416990041732788, "span": {"begin": 891, "end": 903}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9657416939735413, "span": {"begin": 908, "end": 917}}, {"id": ["mim:139300", "mesh:C537436"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "cyp19a1a-deficient", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.4690020978450775, "span": {"begin": 923, "end": 941}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "cyp19a1a", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9952027797698975, "span": {"begin": 923, "end": 931}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9266366362571716, "span": {"begin": 1038, "end": 1047}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9797534346580505, "span": {"begin": 1055, "end": 1064}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003022"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "clotrimazole", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990097284317017, "span": {"begin": 1075, "end": 1087}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fathead minnows", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.7081707715988159, "span": {"begin": 1157, "end": 1172}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:90988"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Pimephales promelas", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.943018913269043, "span": {"begin": 1174, "end": 1193}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "zebrafish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9622684717178345, "span": {"begin": 1199, "end": 1208}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:7955"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Danio rerio", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.978733241558075, "span": {"begin": 1210, "end": 1221}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9771624207496643, "span": {"begin": 1235, "end": 1244}}, {"id": ["mesh:C045362"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "prochloraz", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9979962110519409, "span": {"begin": 1255, "end": 1265}}], "text": "Studies with fish deficient in aromatase (knock-out experiments) as well as studies with&nbsp;known inhibitors of aromatase activity have shown increased occurrence of males.    Several studies with zebrafish (Danio rerio) using&nbsp; the model aromatase inhibitor fadrozole administered via the diet&nbsp;during early development resulted&nbsp;in a predominant male population&nbsp;(Fenske et al. 2004; Uchida et al. 2004; Thresher et al.&nbsp;2011).  Other&nbsp;studies exposing early life-stage zebrafish via water to fadrozole also resulted in male-skewed populations (Luzio et al. 2015; Luzio et al. 2016; Luzio et al. 2016; Muth-K&ouml;hne et al. 2016).  Dietary exposure of Nile tilapia (Oreochromis niloticus) to the aromatase inhibitor exemetane during early development resulted in 100% males in treated fish (Ruksana et al., 2010)  In knockout studies of the aromatase gene using Nile tilapia and zebrafish, all cyp19a1a-deficient fish developed as males&nbsp;(Lau et al. 2016; Yin et al. 2017; Zhang et al. 2017)  Exposure of zebrafish to the aromatase inhibitor clotrimazole induced male-skewed sex ratios&nbsp;(Brown et al. 2015)  Exposure of fathead minnows (Pimephales promelas) and zebrafish (Danio rerio)&nbsp;to the aromatase inhibitor prochloraz skewed sex-ratios to&nbsp;males in a dose-dependent manner&nbsp;(Thorpe et al.&nbsp;2011; Holbech et al.&nbsp;2012).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:29:13 +0000 2026"}